President Joseph R. Biden, Jr. will award the Medal of Honor to three soldiers for their acts of gallantry and bravery. Sergeant First Class Alwyn C. Cashe will receive the award posthumously for his heroic actions in Iraq in 2005, where he saved the lives of his fellow soldiers while sustaining severe burns. Sergeant First Class Christopher A. Celiz will also receive the award posthumously for his actions in Afghanistan in 2018, where he exposed himself to enemy fire to protect his team and ensure the safe evacuation of a wounded soldier. Master Sergeant Earl D. Plumlee will be awarded the Medal of Honor for his actions in Afghanistan in 2013, where he engaged multiple insurgents and saved the lives of his comrades. The Medal of Honor is awarded to members of the Armed Forces who demonstrate exceptional bravery and self-sacrifice in the face of great danger.